## §B. Corporate + catalog modeling (new — slots in as v2 §4.0)

Two parallel hierarchies live in the graph; both are real, both are needed.

**Canonical corporate (annual report, effective-dated):**

```
:Company {name:"JPMC"}
  -[:HAS_BUSINESS_SEGMENT {effective_from, effective_to}]->
:BusinessSegment {code:"CCB"|"CIB"|"AWM"|"Corp"}
```

Pre-Q2-2024 has CCB, CIB, CB, AWM. Post-Q2-2024 has CCB, CIB, AWM, Corp. Edges carry `effective_from` / `effective_to` so a historical query (e.g., "who owned this app on 2024-01-15") returns the right segment.

**Internal product catalog (Oracle source):**

```
:BusinessSegment -[:HAS_LOB]-> :CatalogLOB {lob_id, code:"AWMCIB"|"CCB"|"CT"|"HR"|"ET"|...}
:CatalogLOB     -[:HAS_PRODUCT_LINE]-> :ProductLine
:ProductLine    -[:HAS_PRODUCT]-> :Product {product_id}
:Product        -[:HAS_APPLICATION]-> :Application {seal_id}
:Application    -[:HAS_DEV_TEAM]-> :DevTeam {team_id}
```

Catalog LOBs (AWMCIB, CT, HR, ET) don't 1:1 align with corporate segments. Reconciliation:

```
:CatalogLOB -[:RECONCILES_TO {confidence, source}]-> :BusinessSegment
```

`AWMCIB` → splits across `AWM` and `CIB` with `confidence < 1.0` and `source='manual'`. The graph keeps both views; queries pick which lens to use.

**Refresh cadence**: catalog hierarchy refreshes weekly or monthly from Oracle. Applications are the most stable (years). See §I.

